post.attachment_title: Schiff on NBC Meet The Press: “We Are Going to Find Out” If Whitaker Interferes with Mueller
post.attachment_description:
On Sunday, November 11, Rep. Adam Schiff (D-CA) joined Chuck Todd on NBC's Meet the Press to discuss the firing of Jeff Sessions and questionable appointment of Matthew Whitaker as Acting Attorney General in charge of overseeing the Mueller probe. Schiff also discussed how Democrats will govern in the House, as well as the disastrous California wildfires and the federal response.

During the interview, Schiff said: “I want to make this very clear, if he doesn't recuse himself, if he has any involvement whatsoever in this Russia probe, we are going to find out whether he made commitments to the President about the probe, whether he is serving as a back channel to the President or his lawyers about the probe, whether he's doing anything to interfere with the probe. Mr. Whitaker needs to understand that he will be called to answer and any role that he plays will be exposed to the public. We don't want there to be any ambiguity about that.”
post.name: Adam B. Schiff

post.attachment_title: Rep. Schiff on MSNBC: We Will Discover Any Attempt to Obstruct, and Hold Them Accountable
post.attachment_description:
On Thursday, November 9, Rep. Adam Schiff (D-CA) joined Chris Hayes on MSNBC's All In to discuss Trump's decision to fire Attorney General Jeff Sessions and appoint Matthew Whitaker as the Acting Attorney General. Schiff also discussed how House Democrats will discover any attempt to obstruct the Mueller investigation, and hold those who do accountable. 

Schiff said: "The first thing we can do and did do in the last 24 hours is issue orders to the relevant agencies they have to preserve the evidence. Probably the most powerful thing we can do right now is make it abundantly clear we will demand answers when we do possess those gavels. If there is any effort to obstruct or subvert justice here we will find out about it and people will be held to account. That ought to be made crystal clear from this point. I would also urge my Republican colleagues to do something they have thus far shown unwillingness to do, stand up to this president and defend the rule of law. They know as well as we do this new appointee is not qualified for this position, only qualified by virtue of very political and partisan comments he has made which have endeared him to the president. We ought to act now legislatively to protect Bob Mueller and more broadly, protect the rule of law.”
post.name: Adam B. Schiff

post.attachment_title: Rep. Schiff on CNN: We Will Work to Protect Mueller Investigation
post.attachment_description:
On Thursday, November 8, Rep. Adam Schiff (D-CA) joined Jake Tapper on CNN's The Lead to discuss the President's decision to fire Attorney General Jeff Sessions and appoint Matt Whitaker in his place. Schiff also noted that Democrats have made their "first move" in protecting special counsel Robert Mueller's investigation by sending letters ordering top Trump administration officials to preserve documents connected to the probe.

"But if the President effectively undermines the rule of law and causes the special counsel to be fired or an abrupt or partisan end to this investigation, then it will fall on Congress to find out the facts itself, to get those facts from the Justice Department, to continue our own investigation so that we can tell the country exactly what happened," Schiff said
post.name: Adam B. Schiff

post.attachment_title: 'Vermont Day' at the Edward Kennedy Institute in Boston
post.attachment_description: I am delighted that hundreds of Vermont students have participated in trips organized by my office to visit the Edward Kennedy Institute in Boston.  The non-partisan Kennedy Institute offers innovative programming on the legislative process and how our government works. Students take on the role of a Senator, introducing and debating legislation in a full-scale replica of the U.S. Senate chamber.  It is a wonderful opportunity for high school students to think about what issues are important to them, as well as how to be critical thinkers, work together and bring about positive change in our country. To learn more about “Vermont Days” at the Kennedy Institute, click on this short video or call my office for more information.
post.name: Bernard Sanders

post.attachment_title: Moul Responds to Audit of Susquehanna River Basin Commission
post.attachment_description: I joined Pennsylvania Auditor General Eugene DePasquale and some of my House colleagues at a recent Capitol news conference at which the auditor general released the findings of audits on the Susquehanna and Delaware River Basin Commissions. A few years ago, I raised questions about these interstate compacts, which are largely unchecked and abusing their regulatory authority. The audits show the commissions, which receive taxpayer funding, inappropriately used taxpayer money for lavish meals and alcohol, and for gift cards to reward employees. I will be taking action to increase transparency, provide legislative oversight and other measures to make the commissions more accountable to taxpayers.
post.name: Dan Moul

post.attachment_title: Salute to Arkansas Veterans - Kenneth Ziemer
post.attachment_description:
U.S. Senator John Boozman (R-AR) recognized the service and sacrifice of Vietnam veteran Kenneth Ziemer in ‘Salute to Veterans,’ a series recognizing the military service of Arkansans.

Ziemer now calls Yellville, Arkansas home, but he grew up in Wisconsin. He was working as a medical research assistant at the Veterans Hospital in Madison, WI when he received his draft notice. “I was kind of expecting it,” he said. Joining the Army fulfilled his belief that “every male owed it to their country, at least two years of military service.”

He studied to be a pharmacy specialist and served in Nha Trang, Vietnam as a member of the 523rd Field Hospital. He used his knowledge of chemistry to manufacture medicines, cough syrup, suntan lotion and other products in short supply on the base. 

One of his favorite things to do while in Vietnam was visit the local orphanage. He was passionate about continuing to help the children and missionaries in the area so he took Vietnamese lessons in hopes of returning to work with them after his service was complete.
post.name: John Boozman
